{
  "text": "The first site of blood production in mouse conceptus is the yolk sac (YS) which is a bilayered membrane that surrounds the developing embryo (see Figure 2 ). Haematopoietic activity occurs in the mesodermal layer of the vascularised visceral yolk sac (VYS), which contains blood vessels and haematopoietic cells. In addition to the extraembryonic mesoderm, the VYS is also composed of an outer epithelial layer of extraembryonic visceral endoderm (VE) made of columnar epithelial cells with a brush border [CITATION_1] . The VE layer of the YS has a large absorptive surface and is involved in embryonic nutrition [CITATION_2] . In addition to its role in transporting substances between the maternal and foetal environments, VE cells also contribute to haematopoiesis by secreting factors that induce commitment of mesodermal progenitors to the hematovascular fate [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . The developing endothelium and haematopoietic cells are in very close proximity to the visceral endodermal cells [CITATION_5] . The VE itself is derived from an extraembryonic endodermal progenitor. The specification of VE identity is dependent upon the extraembryonic endodermal cells being exposed to bone morphogenetic protein-4 (Bmp4), leading to gene expression changes resulting in haematopoietic supportive activity [CITATION_6] . Coculture of haematopoietic progenitors with YS-derived endodermal cell lines results in expansion of haematopoietic cells in vitro [CITATION_7] . The transcription factor GATA4 is critical to VE formation [CITATION_8] . Embryonic stem (ES) cells lacking GATA4 are unable to form blood islands demonstrating the role of the VE in haematopoietic cell induction [CITATION_9] . Factors secreted by the VE can induce the primitive ectoderm (which is fated to become brain) to be respecified to become haematopoietic leading to epsilon ( )-haemoglobin expression [CITATION_10] . Indian Hedgehog (Ihh) produced by the VE activates expression of bone morphogenic protein-4 (Bmp4) in neighbouring mesodermal cells leading to haematopoietic initiation and patterning [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . Ihh also regulates vascular endothelial growth factor receptor 1 and 2 (VEGFR-1 and VEGFR-2) expression [CITATION_13] . While both layers of the YS produce VEGF, mesodermal VEGF is unable to induce blood cell formation [CITATION_14] . VEGF produced by the VE however is critical in blood and endothelial cell development in the YS demonstrating a clear role for the VE in the first haematopoietic niche [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] .",
